[1] Cholera - Tanzania (Dar es Salaam)
Date: Tue, 10 Jan 2006 16:50:31 +0000 (GMT)
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: IRIN [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/c0ec2a1fbdef2889a49834b0df51966f.htm>

At least 52 cases of cholera have been reported in parts of the
Tanzanian commercial capital, Dar es Salaam, over the last month, a
city official said on Tue, 8 Jan 2006.
"We are worried over more new cases although we have warned the
people to adhere to rules of hygiene, including boiling drinking
water, use of toilets and washing hands with soap," Gaston Makwembe,
the Dar es Salaam City Information Officer, said.
However, he said an acute shortage of water due to drought could be
one of the reasons for increased cases of cholera because people use
water from ponds and other unsafe sources.
Makwembe said, so far, none of the reported cases had been fatal. He
said those admitted to various centers were treated and discharged.
--
