[2] Cholera - Zimbabwe
Date: Mon, 9 Jan 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promedm@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters.com [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L0954309.htm>

The death toll from a cholera outbreak in Zimbabwe has risen to 14,
with another dozen people in hospital in the capital showing symptoms
of the disease, the official Herald newspaper said on Mon, 9 Jan
2006. State media had reported on Fri, 6 Jan 2006, that cholera had
claimed 11 lives in the rural districts of Buhera, Chikomba and
Chivhu in the last 2 weeks and on Mon, 9 Jan 2006, the Herald said 3
more cholera deaths had been recorded in Harare.
"At least 12 people have been detained...for cholera treatment (in
Harare) ... 4 have since tested positive for cholera," the paper
said, adding that a patient from the poor township of Dzivarasekwa
was in critical condition. Health officials were not immediately
available for comment.
Last week the Herald said over 180 cholera cases had been reported in
Buhera, Chikomba and Chivhu, but that the situation was under
control. Zimbabwe has seen several outbreaks of cholera and other
diseases over the last few years, putting further strain on a health
system that has all but broken down as the country suffers an
economic crisis that has hampered importation of essential drugs and
equipment. The latest outbreak is particularly worrisome as
Zimbabwe's cities grapple with broken-down sewer systems and failure
by municipal authorities to collect refuse from residential areas,
citing a chronic shortage of fuel.
--
