[4] Cholera - Rwanda (Masaka district)
Date: Sun, 8 Jan 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The New Times (Kigali)
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200601090094.html>

The recent outbreak of Cholera in areas of Kigali City (formerly
Masaka District) had by Sat, 7 Jan 2006, claimed 17 lives. According
to the newly appointed Kigali Acting Executive Secretary Fidel
Ndayisaba, the epidemic had also led to the hospitalization of 150
people in the area.
"We are facing a serious outbreak of cholera; so far, over 150 people
have been admitted in Masaka Hospital, while 80 have already received
treatment and have been discharged. 70 are still admitted in the
hospital," Ndayisaba, who said the disease erupted in the last week
of Dec 2005, told The New Times in an exclusive interview Sat, 7 Jan
2006. He attributed the cause to the use of contaminated water from
Nyabarongo river, adding that most of the people who died had not
taken medication.
Ndayisaba, who is still catching up with the challenges in the city,
however said that Electrogaz is expediting repairs on the water pipes
to Masaka. "We have tried to supply enough clean water to the area by
the help of trucks from the City Council water, CHK [Centre
Hospitalier de Kigali], Police, army and volunteers," he said,
adding: "The trucks are used to transport and supply tap water to the
area as the pipelines are still under repair."
Early last week the official in charge of Masaka Hospital, Sister
Maria Gorreti Maama said the disease had claimed 10 lives in the
former sectors of Rusheshe and Ayabaraya in the former district of
Kabuga. She was also quoted as saying that the first case was
reported on 29 Dec 2005.
[Byline: Edwin Musoni]
--
