[5] Cholera, school closures - Rwanda
Date: Wed, 11 Jan 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The New Times (Kigali) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200601110059.html>

All primary and secondary schools in 3 sectors have been ordered not
to re-open for the new academic year due to the cholera epidemic that
has hit the area.
In Masaka sector alone, 3 primary schools, a nursery school and 2
secondary schools will not open, according to Adalbert Rukebanuka,
the area's acting Executive Secretary. The affected schools include
Ayabaraya Primary school, Rusheshe Primary School and Ecole Primaire
de Masaka and a nun-run nursery.
The secondary schools include Ecole Infirmiere de Masaka and Ecole
Technique Libre Sainte Emmanuel. The move is a directive from the
ministries of health and education to combat the cholera outbreak,
according to a source.
Rukebanuka also disclosed that local bars and market stalls selling
fresh fruits, drinks and vegetables have already been ordered to
close. However, there are fears that the area may consequently be
affected by hunger as residents fail to sell or buy agricultural produce.
Masaka sector has recorded the highest number of cholera cases. 18
have already died and over 100 people hospitalized in nearby
hospitals and dispensaries. Latest reports indicate that 6 more
people have died of cholera in the neighboring area of Bugesera.
Residents of the affected area have been advised not to drink water
from the Nyabarongo River, which is said to be contaminated. All the
affected areas border the river.
[Byline: Dean Karemera]
